    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-09-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-09-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="445"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d445">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Dupuy de Lôme</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-09-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 27, 1895</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 39.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>. I have the honor to advise you that on the
                    receipt of your note of the 25th instant, as to the apprehended departure of an
                    expedition <pb facs="0469" n="1203" xml:id="pg_1203"/> for Cuba from the
                    neighborhood of Cedar Keys, I at once inclosed a copy to the Secretary of the
                    Navy, to whom I suggested the desirability of such telegraphic orders to the
                    commander of the United States cruiser then at Key West as would instruct and
                    enable him to prevent such violations of the neutrality laws of the United
                    States as seemed to be contemplated.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Richard Olney.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
